The reference is to the so-called turris Maecenatis on the Esquiline, from which Nero afterwards watched the burning of Rome, and which had a commanding view over Rome (see lines 11, 12) and the neighbourhood. 11.·mirari . . . This terse description of a great capital as observed from some point of vantage is inimitable. The wealth, the smoke, the riches, the roar of London, as seen say from St. Paul’s, might well in their combined effect make the beholder ‘ marvel ' (mirari). 14. mundae. The adjective indicates the presence of taste but the absence of extravagance. Horace defines mundus (S. 2. 2. 65), as applied to a host, as a just mean between luxurious excess and sordid neglect.
